  "title": "Posterior abdominal wall",
  "body_html": "<div class=\"table-responsive\"><table class = \"tlarge table table-striped table-bordered\"  data-role=\"table\" id=\"tableid1\" ><thead><tr><th><b>Muscle</b></th><th>Innervation & Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><b>Psoas Major</b></td><td><ul><li>Innervation: Lumbar Plexus anterior rami L1-L4</li><li>Action: Flexion and medial rotation of femur</td></tr><tr><td><b>Quadratus Lumborum</b></td><td><ul><li>Innervation: T12-L4 spinal nerves</li><li>Action: Lateral flexion of vertebral column</td></tr><tr><td><b>Iliacus</b></td><td><ul><li>Innervation: Femoral nerve</li><li>Action: Flexion and medial rotation of thigh</td></tr></tbody></table></div></li></ul><br />Note iliacus and psoas are sometimes referred to together as iliopsoas as they have the same insertion onto the lesser trochanter and the same action on the femur. <br /><br />Also note that the direction of rotation is controversial. Many texts say psoas and iliacus are lateral rotators. Some studies say flexion is usually in the neutral line (i.e. without rotation). The RCEM however considers the iliopsoas muscle group to be medial rotators and as they are marking the exam we will go with them.<br /><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb137b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb137.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/iliacus'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb137b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Diagram illustrating iliacus and psoas major</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb138b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb138.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/quadratus lumborum muscle'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb138b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Anterior view illustrating relations of quadratus lumborum</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti256b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti256.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Anterior view illustrating relations of quadratus lumborum</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti257b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti257.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Diagram illustrating relations of quadratus lumborum on cross section. Note the lateral position of transversus abdominus and medial relation of psoas major</div></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">1</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">1</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Anatomy</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Abdomen & pelvis</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\n<div class=\"table-responsive\"><table class = \"tlarge table table-striped table-bordered\"  data-role=\"table\" id=\"tableid1\" ><thead><tr><th><b>Muscle</b></th><th>Innervation & Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><b>Psoas Major</b></td><td><ul><li>Innervation: Lumbar Plexus anterior rami L1-L4</li><li>Action: Flexion and medial rotation of femur</td></tr><tr><td><b>Quadratus Lumborum</b></td><td><ul><li>Innervation: T12-L4 spinal nerves</li><li>Action: Lateral flexion of vertebral column</td></tr><tr><td><b>Iliacus</b></td><td><ul><li>Innervation: Femoral nerve</li><li>Action: Flexion and medial rotation of thigh</td></tr></tbody></table></div></li></ul><br />Note iliacus and psoas are sometimes referred to together as iliopsoas as they have the same insertion onto the lesser trochanter and the same action on the femur. <br /><br />Also note that the direction of rotation is controversial. Many texts say psoas and iliacus are lateral rotators. Some studies say flexion is usually in the neutral line (i.e. without rotation). The RCEM however considers the iliopsoas muscle group to be medial rotators and as they are marking the exam we will go with them.<br /><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb137b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb137.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/iliacus'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a da